Yes, this statement can be interpreted in terms of sets: 
Let G = {All Gold} 
M = {Metal} 
B = {Black}
We know that G is a subset of M (since all gold is considered to be metal). We also know that B is a subset of M (some metals are known to be black). So we can conclude that there must exist an intersection between G and B i.e. at least one element from G which belongs to B. Therefore, Some Gold is Black. Hence, The Final Answer would be yes.
